Once average willingness to pay for costs and benefits has been obtained, it has to be aggregated across the relevant population of those who benefit and those who lose. With this, it is then possible to determine whether the policy should be adopted on efficiency grounds. The first rule that may come up is to approve any policy that achieves a Pareto improvement, i.e., that makes some people better off while leaving nobody worse off. However, policies with this characteristic are exceptional. A less restrictive condition for a policy to pass a cost–benefit analysis is that the value of aggregate benefits outweighs that of aggregate costs. If this is the case, those who benefit can compensate the losers and still be better off. This is called a potential Pareto improvement. A general formula for determining if a project is acceptable under this criterion would be:∑i,twiWTPiG1+st-∑i,twiWTPiL1+st≥0.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathop \sum \limits_{i,t} w_{i} WTP_{i}^{G} \left( {1 + s} \right)^{t} - \mathop \sum \limits_{i,t} w_{i} WTP_{i}^{L} \left( {1 + s} \right)^{t} \ge 0.$$\end{document}

